article.description: Pee Wee Johnson's basket from the top of the arc with 0.4 seconds remaining lifted the Orlando Miracle past the Charlotte Sting 65-63 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Johnson's last-second jumper lifts Miracle
article.linkText: Miracle top Charlotte with big shot from Pee Wee
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Pee Wee Johnson's basket from the top of
the arc with 0.4 seconds remaining lifted the Orlando Miracle past
the Charlotte Sting 65-63 on Thursday night.

	   Johnson finished with 16 points for Orlando (13-13), which won
its third straight and beat Charlotte for the first time in three
games this season.

	   "I knew what the situation was,'' Johnson said. "We were
either going to win or go to overtime.''

	   Allison Feaster led the Sting (14-12) with 14 points.

	   The winning play developed when Orlando inbounded the ball with
11.6 seconds left and quickly got the ball to Johnson. She stood
just inside the half-court line for a few seconds before driving
toward the basket and launching her game-winning shot.

	   "I knew when I let it go it was in,'' Johnson said. "I had a
clear shot and it felt good leaving my hand. I shot from the spot I
planned to shoot from.''

	   Orlando coach Dee Brown felt confident with the Johnson handling
the ball.

	   "The ball was Shannon's to do whatever she wanted to with,''
Brown said. "We'll take it any way we can. It was easily the
biggest shot of the season for us.''

	   The game appeared headed for overtime when the Sting's Charlotte
Smith hit a 3-pointer with 12.1 seconds left to tie it at 63.

	   "We let it get away,'' Charlotte coach Anne Donovan said. "We
had a 10-point lead and should have been able to hold it. It's a
very disappointing loss.''

	   Katie Douglas put Orlando ahead for the first time in the second
half, 61-60, with 1:16 to play. Johnson then added to Orlando's
lead with a basket with 24.6 seconds left.

	   The Miracle tied it at 56 on a 3-pointer by Douglas with 5:06 to
play, capping a 16-6 run that began with 11 minutes to play and
Orlando trailing 50-40.
